
⸻

FG-231 — Type-Volume Certificate (Words • Exclusions • Rule)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Your brief dies without a clean FRAP/local word-count certificate.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: State exact count, tool used, exclusions (captions/tables/certs), and the rule (e.g., FRAP 32(g)); mirror Title metadata and filename.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 4-line certificate for your opening brief.
	•	✅ Model Response: “This brief contains 12,994 words per word-processing system, excluding captions/tables/certificates, under FRAP 32(g).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: A precise number beats “about.”
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small odometer reading “12,994” next to a rule tag.

⸻

FG-232 — Statement of the Case (Pins, Not Adjectives)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Facts persuade only with pins and neutral verbs.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 5–8 short sentences; each has one pin (Dkt/Ex/Tr); no motives, no adverbs; end with posture triangle (statute/clock/copies) if needed.
	•	📝 Assignment: Rewrite your fact section into 8 sentences with one pin each.
	•	✅ Model Response: “On 07/31 mail delivered 09:42 (Ex A:1). On 08/02 court stated it would not reach harm (Dkt 18 at 2).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Neutral facts outlive rhetoric.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Eight short lines; each ends with a pin tag.

⸻

FG-233 — Questions Presented (Two, Neutral, ≤18 Words)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Two answerable questions guide the panel to your order.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Keep each Q neutral, rule-framed, with no facts; order them by signability; mirror them in headings.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft two QPs ≤18 words, neutral voice.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Must courts make factor-tied findings before denying preliminary relief?” “Is ‘harm not reached’ reversible under [circuit] law?”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Small questions win big orders.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two clean Q cards feeding a signature strip.

⸻

FG-234 — Standards Page Template (One Line Each + Cite)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Put De Novo / Abuse / Clear Error in one scan.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One line per standard + controlling cite; label issues to standards; link each argument paragraph to its SoR.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build the SoR box you can paste into any brief.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Abuse: wrong test (cite). De novo: legal rule (cite). Clear error: firm conviction (cite).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Lens first, view second.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Three lens icons stacked over a page.

⸻

FG-235 — Summary of Argument (≤150 Words, Order-Driven)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Summarize what signs, not everything you know.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 3 sentences: standard, two pins, two-line order; no quotations; no adjectives.
	•	📝 Assignment: Reduce your summary to ≤150 words with SoR + pins + relief.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Abuse; court used wrong test; harm not reached (Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2). Relief: remand 21 days for findings (a–d).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Summary = pre-order.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small paragraph pointing to an order card.

⸻

FG-236 — Record Statement (What’s In • Where • Neutral)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Tell the court what record exists and where—once.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Identify docket range, transcripts (dates), exhibits (tabs); state legend (“PDF pages”); no argument; hash the appendix guide.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-line record statement with a legend line.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Record: Dkts 1–102; Tr. 07/21, 08/02; Ex A–D (Appx Tabs). Cites are to PDF pages.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Orientation prevents detours.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A contents page with a fingerprint footer.

⸻

FG-237 — Preservation Map (Raised • Ruled • Pin)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: If it wasn’t presented, it isn’t reviewed. Prove preservation.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Grid: Issue • Where raised (Doc/pg) • Ruling (or refusal) • Pin; attach to appendix; cite in Standards.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 6-row preservation table for your brief.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Harm — Mot. PI (Dkt 14:3) — ‘not reached’ — Dkt 18:2.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Visibility = credibility.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small grid with check marks under “Raised/Ruled.”

⸻

FG-238 — Scope & Carve-Outs Paragraph (Who • What • Sunset)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Relief survives review when precisely scoped.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Identify who (parties only), what (¶/claim), sunset (21d), status date; include vendor carve-outs where needed.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft your scope line in one sentence.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Stay ¶3 as to parties only; carve-out vendors X/Y; sunset 21 days; status at day 14.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Narrow asks get green checks.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A bracket around one paragraph, with a small “vendors” tag.

⸻

FG-239 — Certificate Suite (Service • Type-Volume • Compliance)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Close with all certificates, clean and consistent.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Include service (method/date/list), type-volume (exact words + rule), and any compliance statements (PDF/UA, bookmarks, Title).
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft your three certificates for the current filing.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Served via ECF/mail 08/20; words 12,994 under FRAP 32(g); PDF/A, Title ‘Opening Brief v3’, bookmarks mirroring H2s.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Certificates are the last impression.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Three small seals in a row.

⸻

FG-240 — Clerk Cover Letter (Neutral • Enclosures • Ask)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A short cover letter smooths intake and fixes errors faster.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Caption; purpose (file/replace/correct); enclosures list (hash if helpful); neutral one-line ask; contact info; cc counsel.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line cover letter for your next filing.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Purpose: replace Ex A due to scan error; enclosures listed; SHA-256 …; request suppression of prior link; contact below.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Professional tone moves gates.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A one-page letter with a small “enclosures” box.